<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="73" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="73">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" genus="Dendrostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dendrostoma aurorae" order="Diaporthales" pageId="6" pageNumber="73" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="aurorae">Dendrostoma aurorae</taxonomicName>
was discovered on stems of dying chestnut trees and appears morphologically similar to the chestnut blight pathogen, 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cryphonectriaceae" genus="Cryphonectria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cryphonectria parasitica" order="Diaporthales" pageId="6" pageNumber="73" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="parasitica">Cryphonectria parasitica</taxonomicName>
. However, these two diaporthalean pathogens can be distinguished by the existence of a central column inside the conidiomata of 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" genus="Dendrostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dendrostoma aurorae" order="Diaporthales" pageId="6" pageNumber="73" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="aurorae">Dendrostoma aurorae</taxonomicName>
. In the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" genus="Dendrostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dendrostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="6" pageNumber="73" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Dendrostoma</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. aurorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="aurorae">D. aurorae</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. chinensis" pageId="6" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="chinensis">D. chinensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. shandongense" pageId="6" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="shandongense">D. shandongense</taxonomicName>
by the existence of an obvious central column.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
